passages.text: ADSK's 2Q beat and FY26 raise were straightforward, so we focus this note on three forward looking modelling points: (1) FY29 margins of \(41\%\) ; (2) our assumptions in FY27 as the model shift nears completion; (3) our estimate for \(\) 14+\(in FY29 EPS, which underpins our\) \ \(385\) PT. More below...

ADSK's 2Q26 upside and higher FY26 guide is straightforward, so we focus this front page on three forward- looking modelling points: (1) FY29 EBIT margin guide of \(41\%\) as- reported is driven mostly by S&M leverage and has flexibility in different growth scenarios - we introduce FY29 estimates that assume \(8 - 9\%\) revenue growth and \(41\%\) margins, driving \(\) 14+\(in EPS; (2) FY27 is an important year in ADSK's transition because it represents the tail end of the revenue benefit, but also continued margin impact - we discuss our math around FY27 revenue (underlying plus estimated\) \ \(160M\) benefit), and margin dynamics further below; (3) 2H26 billings growth is slower than 1H, which we think reflects a normalizing impact from the agency transition as remember Japan transitioned in November 2024 - so we think billings growth could actually be normal in FY27, but think FCF may not benefit as much from OBBBA. Our PT goes to\) \ \(385\) , based on 30x FY29E EPS discounted back one- year at a \(10\%\) WACC.

- Most investable takeaway was the FY29 EBIT margin guide of \(41\%\) as-reported (45% underlying) - we believe most of this expansion will come from S&M; important to note, this seems to have some flexibility around revenue growth - we model \(8 - 9\%\) underlying revenue growth through FY29 with a path to \(41\%\) margins, getting us \(\) 14+\(in FY29 EPS and underpinning our.\) \ \(385\) PT. We think the most investable takeaway from ADSK's 2Q call was that it expects FY29 EBIT margins to be \(41\%\) on an as-reported basis post the agency model transition, \(\) 40\(about\) 45\%\(on an underlying basis pro-forma for the model transition. With the\) 37\%\(guide for FY26, that reflects about 400 bps of expansion over the next 3 years - while we did not get where exactly that expansion would come from, we believe the bulk of it should come from sales & marketing leverage, as the go-to-market initiatives like growing - store, realigning channel incentives around new business versus renewals, and channel consolidation, should drive slower S&M growth. There will still be operating leverage across R&D and G&A, but again we think the bulk of this 400 bps in margin expansion will come from S&M. Importantly, ADSK noted that this margin target was flexible, meaning it would be achievable in a range of growth scenarios - that's refreshing for ADSK veterans that remember long-term targets where circumstances changed. To that end, we are introducing

FY29 estimates which assume 8- 9% revenue growth and 41% EBIT margins to get to \(\) 14+\(in FY29 EPS.

- **Thoughts on our FY27 model: (1) we model ~9% underlying revenue growth plus ~\)160M in transition benefit - that benefit plus the benefits in FY25 and FY26E add up to ~\)600M contra-revenue by our estimates; (2) margin expansion in FY27E will not be a linear path to 41% in FY29E - remember FY27 will have almost all revenue shifted to lower margin agency.** FY27 is an important year in ADSK's transition because it represents the tail end of the revenue benefit, but there will continue to a margin impact, which is why ADSK specifically called out that the path to 41% in FY29 would not be linear, particularly when talking about FY27. More specifically on the top-line, we model FY27 revenue of \(\)7,845M\(or 11% growth - within this, we assume underlying growth of ~9% (ex model impact), and then layer in -\)160M in transition benefit. Stepping back, we get to this \(\)160M\(estimate by compiling the quarterly revenue benefits since 2Q25 when the agency transition started in North America - that sum since then is -\)254M, and we will lap the last geography moving to agency in November 2025, so we estimate by end of FY26, the accumulated benefit over two years would be -\)440M. Recall, when this transition was first announced, ADSK noted that about \(\)600M\(in contra-revenue would shift back into revenue - so keeping that number unchanged minus\)440M\(across the last two years, gets us to\)160M\(in FY27E. From a margin perspective, remember as more revenue comes from the agency model, the more it will weigh on margins (and hence that commentary on the ADSK call) - so we model about 100 bps of margin improvement, with as-reported margins at -38%.

- **Other modelling tidbits: (1) 2H26 billings growth is normalizing post the transition - remember Japan was the last geography to shift in November 2024, so FY27 billings we think grows at normal rates; (2) cash taxes will not be significant benefit in FY27, but restructuring also should not repeat - we think more FCF margin expansion will happen in FY28-29.** Billings growth accelerated in 2Q, but implied 2H guide reflects materially slower growth and while some of that is prudence, we also think some of it is normalization after this agency transition. Remember, Japan was the last geography to shift to the new model in November 2024 - so with mostly annual contracts, the impact of the transition on billings will mostly normalize by November 2025 by our estimates. In fact, this means that the transition impact to billings normalizes about a year earlier than the impact to revenue - which makes sense given the ratability. Therefore looking forward, we think FY27 billings growth will grow at their natural underlying rate, or about 9% by our estimates with little/no impact from the transition. The one curve ball in FY27 might be cash taxes, which is unusual because OBBBA is largely taking up FCF estimates on lower cash taxes - it may be different for ADSK because this year is already expected to have a \(\)130-150M\(cash tax benefit, so there may not be much of an OBBBA benefit in FY27 as a result. That said, there probably will not be another restructuring charge, but these are just a couple of the puts and takes to FY27E FCF.**

Valuation Methodology: Our price target of \(385 is based on - 30x our FY29 EPS of\) 14.23, discounted back at a 10% WACC.

Risks which May Impede the Achievement of the Barclays Research Valuation and Price Target: We see three downside risks to our Overweight rating. First, if ADSK is unable to reach FY23 goals of 16- 18% revenue CAGR, 40% operating margin and \(2.4B in FCF, estimates could deteriorate causing the stock to underperform. Second, while there is some cannibalization expected from new licensing options, if this is greater than expected, estimates could go down. Third, ADSK sells into an economically sensitive customer base, so if the fragile recovery were to deteriorate, estimates could go down, and the stock could underperform.
